Compare base case curtailment vs CAISO 2016 curtailment data¶

  • CAISO 2016 curtailment data downloaded from http://www.caiso.com/informed/Pages/ManagingOversupply.aspx
  • data are in 5-min intervals; data aggregated to 1 hour intervals
  • simulation data are from base case with scenario_name = 'western_scenario_Update01'

Summary¶

Curtailment values from our simulations are at least 2 orders of magnitude smaller than the CAISO curtailment values (depending on what curtailment metric is being counted). The simulation's smaller values come from the combination of (1) much smaller curtailment values and (2) much less frequent curtailment. Although the CAISO demand ('Load') values are smaller than the simulation demand data (and smaller demand can lead to more curtailment), the difference is not large enough to explain the difference.

Possible sources of the differences include available energy forecast errors, ramp rate differences, non-physical (e.g., does not follow laws of physics) curtailment practices.

As a sanily check, apply same analysis to Texas data, where the networks can be guaranteed to be more similar.

In [55]:
def get_plant_id(zone, resource):
    plant_id = []
    if zone == 'Western':
        try:
            plant_id = win_data.genbus.groupby('type').get_group(resource).index.values.tolist()
        except KeyError:
            pass
    elif zone == 'California':
        CA = ['Bay Area', 'Central California', 'Northern California',
                'Southeast California', 'Southwest California']
        for load_zone in CA:
            try:
                plant_id += win_data.genbus.groupby(['ZoneName', 'type']).get_group(
                    (load_zone, resource)).index.values.tolist()
            except KeyError:
                pass
    else:
        try:
            plant_id = win_data.genbus.groupby(['ZoneName', 'type']).get_group(
                (zone, resource)).index.values.tolist()
        except KeyError:
            pass
    
    return plant_id

datadir = os.path.join('..','data/')
filename = 'ProductionAndCurtailmentsData-May1_2014-May31_2017.xlsx'
sheets = ['Production','Curtailments']
d0 = pd.read_excel(io=os.path.join(datadir, filename), header=0, sheet_name = sheets)
d1 = {}

for x in sheets:
    d0[x].index = pd.to_datetime(d0[x]['Date'])
    #d0[x]['Date2'] = d0[x].index.date
    d0[x]['Date2'] = pd.to_datetime(d0[x]['Date']).dt.date
    d0[x]['Year'] = pd.to_datetime(d0[x]['Date']).dt.year
    d1[x] = d0[x].loc[d0[x]['Year'] == 2016]

data = pd.merge(d1['Production'], d1['Curtailments'], 
                how = 'left', on = ['Date2','Hour','Interval'],
               left_index=False)
data.index = pd.to_datetime(data['Date_x'])
data.index.rename('LocalTime',inplace=True)
data.drop(columns = ['Date2','Date_x','Date_y','Year_x','Year_y'], inplace=True)

# Remove duplicated time data
data = data[~data.index.duplicated(keep='first')]

# Remove NAs
data.fillna(value=0., inplace=True)

# Raw data are in 5 minute intervals; Resample to hourly data
data_h = data.resample('H').sum()/12.

# Estimate curtailment percent
data_h['solar_curtailed_pc'] = 100.* data_h['Solar Curtailment']/(1.+ data_h['Solar'] + data_h['Solar Curtailment'])
data_h['wind_curtailed_pc'] = 100.* data_h['Wind Curtailment']/(1. + data_h['Wind'] + data_h['Wind Curtailment'])

Aha, CAISO data has lower load than our simulation demand data; why is that?

  • Compare with CISO EIA data; also compare
  • demand obtained by multiplying CA 2016 population * demand per capita
  • demand by multiplying CISO service population * demand per capita

Note that higher load means curtailment is less likely to happen. Demand vs solar/wind curtailment not likely linear function. Also, does demand include demand from houses with solar cells?

Do we overestimate demand? Get CA population and multiply by demand per capita¶

  • demand per capita used in grid construction (Gegner et al 2016, Birchfeld et al 2016) is 2.01kW per person (summer demand from Eastern US population)
  • CA 2016 population is 39.3M
  • Answer - both simulation and CA demand load values are in the right ballpark, and less than expected demand based on Eastern summer data (CA has dryer summers than Eastern US, lower humidity means less air-conditioning; CA load is about 75% of simulation demand, but CAISO says they manage ~80% of CA electric flow.

            'solar_curtailment_hours','solar_curtailment_pc'
           ]
stats = pd.DataFrame(columns = col_names, index = ['CAISO','SIM'])

stats.loc['CAISO']['wind_curtailment_hours'] = data_h.loc[data_h['Wind Curtailment']>0].describe().loc['count']['Wind Curtailment']
stats.loc['CAISO']['solar_curtailment_hours'] = data_h.loc[data_h['Solar Curtailment']>0].describe().loc['count']['Solar Curtailment']

stats.loc['SIM']['wind_curtailment_hours'] = sim_wind.loc[sim_wind['curtailment']>0].describe().loc['count']['curtailment']
stats.loc['SIM']['solar_curtailment_hours'] = sim_solar.loc[sim_solar['curtailment']>0].describe().loc['count']['curtailment']

#Calculate curtailment fractions for the WHOLE YEAR: CAISO
for x in ['Wind','Solar']:
    available = data_h[x +' Curtailment'].sum() + data_h[x].sum()
    generated = data_h[x].sum()
    curtailment = 100 * (available - generated) / available
    stats.loc['CAISO'][x.lower() + '_curtailment_pc'] = curtailment
    print("CAISO Curtailment %s: %.8f %%" % (x, curtailment))
    
#Calculate curtailment fractions for the WHOLE YEAR: BASE CAEE 2016

        stats.loc['SIM'][resource + '_curtailment_pc'] = curtailment
        print("Simulation Curtailment %s/%s: %.8f %%" % (zone, resource, curtailment))
